h:auto height:250 barincrement:50\nPlotArea  = left:35 bottom:15 top:10 right:18\nAlignBars = justify\nDateFormat= yyyy\nPeriod    = from:0 till:154\nTimeAxis  = orientation:vertical\nScaleMajor= unit:year increment:100 start:0\n\nPlotData=\n  color:skyblue width:28\n  bar:2005 from:start till:18 text:18 align:center\n  bar:2006 from:start till:59 text:59 align:center\n  bar:2007 from:start till:79 text:79 align:center\n  bar:2008 from:start till:81 text:81 align:center\n  bar:2009 from:start till:86 text:86 align:center\n  bar:2010 from:start till:87 text:87 align:center\n  bar:2011 from:9 till:92 text:92 align:center\n  bar:2012 from:40 till:99 text:99 align:center\n  bar:2013 from:64 till:116 text:116 align:center\n  bar:2014 from:83 till:118 text:118 align:center\n  bar:2015 from:101 till:120 text:120 align:center\n  bar:2016 from:110 till:138 text:138 align:center\n  bar:2017 from:124 till:136 text:136 align:center\n  bar:2018 from:130 till:154 text:154 align:center\n  bar:2019 from:137 till:154 text:154 align:center\n\n color:green width:28\u2013\n  bar:2011 from:start till:9 text:9 align:center\n  bar:2012 from:start till:40 text:40 align:center\n  bar:2013 from:start till:64 text:64 align:center\n  bar:2014 from:start till:83 text:83 align:center\n  bar:2015 from:start till:101 text:101 align:center\n  bar:2016 from:start till:110 text:110 align:center\n  bar:2017 from:start till:124 text:124 align:center\n  bar:2018 from:start till:130 text:130 align:center\n  bar:2019 from:start till:137 text:137 align:center\n</timeline>\n{{Timeline Legend|colour=skyblue|text=Orders}} {{Timeline Legend|colour=green|text=Deliveries}}\n\nData as of December 31, 2019.\n\n==Incidents==\nOn September 11, 2012, an Airbridge Cargo 747-8F experienced a major engine malfunction that spread a significant amount of metallic debris on the runway. Like in a similar event during pre-flight taxi tests, the low pressure turbine shaft separated and moved the low pressure turbine backwards braking on surrounding hardware (by design to avoid turbine overspeed).<ref name=\"Air Bridge Cargo B748 at Shanghai rejected takeoff\">{{cite web |url=http://avherald.com/h?article=455c2b52&opt=0 |author=Simon Hradecky |title=Incident: Air Bridge Cargo B748 at Shanghai on Sep 11th 2012, rejected takeoff}}</ref> The NTSB issued urgent safety recommendations to the FAA to require ultrasonic scans for midshaft fractures before use of GEnx engines and require repetitive on-wing inspections of the engine to detect cracks before it could reach a critical length.<ref>[https://www.ntsb.gov/news/press-releases/Pages/NTSB_issues_urgent_recommendations_for_GEnx-1B_and_-2B_engines.aspx NTSB issues urgent recommendations for GEnx-1B and -2B engines]</ref>{{importance inline|This is more clear but still not that significant to the aircraft overall.}}\n\nOn July 31, 2013, an [[AirBridgeCargo Airlines|Airbridge Cargo]] 747-8F experienced core engine icing that caused engine malfunctions and damage to three engines near [[Chengdu, China]], while en route to [[Hong Kong]]; the aircraft landed safely at its destination. Boeing and General Electric are working on software changes to mitigate the effects of core engine icing.<ref name=AW_core_icing_incident>{{cite web |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/Article.aspx?id=/article-xml/AW_09_02_2013_p20-610669.xml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213005534/http://www.aviationweek.com/Article.aspx?id=%2Farticle-xml%2FAW_09_02_2013_p20-610669.xml |archivedate=December 13, 2013 |author=Guy Norris |title=Core Engine Icing Strikes Russian 747-8F |date=September 2, 2013 |work=Aviation Week |accessdate=September 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=AH_core_icing_incident>{{cite web |url=http://avherald.com/h?article=46679ba1 |author=Simon Hradecky |title=Incident: Air Bridhe Cargo B748 near Hong Kong on Jul 31st 2013, both left hand engines surged at same time, one right hand engine damaged too |date=n.d. |accessdate=September 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=ATW_core_icing_incident>{{cite web |url=http://atwonline.com/safety/russia-investigate-airbridgecargo-747-8f-engine-incident-boeing-ge |author=Polina Borodina |title=Russia to investigate AirBridgeCargo 747-8F engine incident with Boeing, GE |date=n.d. |accessdate=September 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Specifications==\n[[File:Giant planes comparison - Updated - 2019.svg|thumb|upright=1.2|Comparison between five of the largest aircraft:\n {{legend|#A4B8E8|'''Boeing 747-8'''}}\n {{legend|#E49292|[[Airbus A380-800]]}}\n {{legend|#80DF8B|[[Antonov An-225 Mriya|Antonov An-225 ''Mriya'']]}}\n {{legend|#D6C35B|[[Hughes H-4 Hercules]]}}\n {{legend|#FFC8FF|[[Scaled Composites Stratolaunch|Stratolaunch]]}}\n]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ 747-8 characteristics<ref name=\"747-8_specs\">{{cite web |url= http://www.boeing.com/commercial/747/#/design-highlights/characteristics/ |title= 747-8 characteristics |publisher= Boeing}}</ref>\n! Variant\n! 747-8I\n! 747-8F\n|-\n![[Cockpit]] crew\n| colspan=2| Two\n|-\n![[Airline seat|Seat]] capacity\n| 467 in 3-class\n| 303,700&nbsp;lb / 137.7&nbsp;t\n|-\n!Exit limit<ref name=TCDS>{{cite web |url= http://www.airweb.faa.gov/Regulatory_and_Guidance_Library/rgMakeModel.nsf/0/b3bb8eb44b6d73748625804400536f22/$FILE/A20WE_Rev58.pdf |title= Type Certificate data sheet No. A20WE |date= October 5, 2016 |publisher= FAA}}</ref>\n| 605\n| 8\n|-\n![[Cargo aircraft|Cargo]] volume\n| {{cvt|6,225|cuft|sigfig=3}}\n| {{cvt|30,288|cuft|sigfig=3}}\n|-\n! Length\n| colspan=2| 250&nbsp;ft 2 in / 76.3 m\n|-\n! Height\n| colspan=2| 63&nbsp;ft 6 in / 19.4 m\n|-\n![[Wingspan]]\n| colspan=2| 224&nbsp;ft 7 in / 68.4 m\n|-\n![[Wing]]\n| colspan=2| {{cvt|554|m2}},<ref name=\"flight-tech-desc\">{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/in-focus-boeing-747-8-technical-description-amp-cutaway-378866/ |title= Boeing 747-8 technical description & cutaway |date= 13 November 2012 |work= Flight Global